		<h2 id='wwwcols'>Problem Columns on the World Wide Web</h2>
		<ul>
      <li><a href="http://www.ugcs.caltech.edu/~peterw/math/math.html">Peter Wang's problem of the month</a><br>
This is an olympiad-level problem column published monthly by
      <a href="http://www.ugcs.caltech.edu/~peterw/">Peter T. Wang</a></li>
      
<li><a href="http://www.stolaf.edu/stolaf/depts/math/mathmess/past_week.html">MathMess Problem of Week</a><br>
  This is conducted by <a href="mailto:larson@stolaf.edu">Loren Larson</a> at St. Olaf College.</li>
  
      <li><a href="gopher://gopher.maa.org:70/11/general/Queries">MAA gopher queries</a></li>
  
<li><a href="gopher://gopher.maa.org:70/00/student/Competitions/prob-neal">Richard Neal's
Problem Solving Competition</a><br>
  information only.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.mathsoft.com/">MathSoft</a> publishes
<a href="http://www.mathsoft.com/puzzle.html">MathCad Puzzler</a> each month
which consists of problems selected from Allan Gottlieb's problem column in <cite>Technology Review</cite>.</ul>

    

<h2 id='wwwwprobs'>Mathematics Problems on the World Wide Web</h2>
<ul>

<li><a href="archive/RusMath.txt">The All-Soviet-Union mathematics competitions 1961-1987</a><br>
These have been provided by <a href="mailto:voldemar@wisdom.weizmann.ac.il">Vladimir A. Pertsel</a> who translated them into English.
Also available by <a href="gopher://archives.math.utk.edu:70/59/teaching.materials/contests/rusmath">gopher.</a></li>

<li>The <a href="http://www.civeng.carleton.ca/">Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering at Carleton University</a>
has started a collection of <a href="http://www.civeng.carleton.ca/Problems/">mathematics puzzles</a>.</li>

<li>William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.ugcs.caltech.edu/~peterw/">Peter T. Wang</a> has recent Putnam problems posted at
<a href="http://www.ugcs.caltech.edu/~peterw/putnam.html"> http://www.ugcs.caltech.edu/~peterw/putnam.html</a>.</li>

<li><a href="http://www.math.upenn.edu/~larsen/">Michael Larson</a> has some of the recent Putnam competitions on-line (in PostScript).
See his home page for details. He also lists some <a href="http://www.math.upenn.edu/~larsen/putnam/scores">recent high scores</a></li>

<li>A <a href="gopher://gopher.maa.org:70/00/student/Competitions/Putnam/Putnam%20problems%20and%20solutions">list
of references</a> to where in the American Mathematical Monthly you canfind Putnam Problems and solutions, is maintained by the MAA.</ul>

<li><a href="http://math.berkeley.edu/~desouza/pb.html">University of California at Berkeley Preliminary Ph. D. Examinations</a>
<br>
Brought to you by
Paulo Ney de Souza (desouza@math.berkeley.edu) and
Jorge-Nuno Silva (jnsilva@math.berkeley.edu) of the UC Berkeley
Mathematics Department. Includes problems from 1977 to present.
</L>
			<li><a href="http://www.kalva.demon.co.uk/">Kalva's collection of Maths Problems</a>
			<li><a href="http://www.imo.org.yu/" target="aaa">IMO Compendium</a>
		</U>

<a name="news"></a>
<h2>Newsgroups</h2>

The following newsgroups are devoted to math problems or puzzles
or contain a fair amount of math problems (among other topics).

<ul>
<li><a HREF="news:alt.algebra.help" NAME="alt.algebra.help">alt.algebra.help</a>
<li><a HREF="news:geometry.puzzles" NAME="geometry.puzzles">geometry.puzzles</a>
<li><a HREF="news:rec.puzzles" NAME="rec.puzzles">rec.puzzles</a><br>
The archive to rec.puzzles is located at.
<a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive">
ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive</a>.
The archive has the following subdivisions:
<ul>
<a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/Instructions">
Instructions</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/analysis">analysis puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/arithmetic/">arithmetic puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/combinatorics">combinatorics puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/competition/">competition puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/cryptology">cryptology puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/decision">decision puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/geometry/">geometry puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/group">group puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/induction">induction puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/language/">language puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/logic/">logic puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/physics">physics puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/pickover/">pickover puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/probability">probability puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/real-life">real-life puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/references">references</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/series">series puzzles</a>
| <a href="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet/news.answers/puzzles/archive/trivia">trivia puzzles</a>
</ul>

There is a group of rec.puzzles regulars, who are familiar with the
rec.puzzles archive, and who will respond to queries. To send them a question,
send an email to <a href="mailto:puzzle-oracle@questrel.com">puzzle-oracle@questrel.com</a>.

<li><a href="news:sci.math" NAME="sci.math">sci.math</a><br>
Sections of the <a href="http://daisy.uwaterloo.ca/~alopez-o/math-faq/mathtext/math-faq.html">FAQ</a> (Frequently Asked Questions file) that are of interest to problemists:
<ul>
  <li>Unsolved Problems
  <ul>
    <li>Does there exist a number that is perfect and odd?
    <li>Collatz Problem
  </ul>
  <li>Famous Problems in Mathematics
  <ul>
    <li>The Four Colour Theorem
    <li>The Trisection of an Angle
  </ul>
  <li>Which are the 23 Hilbert Problems?</li>
</ul>  

<li><a href="news:alt.math.iams" name="alt.math.iams">alt.math.iams</a><br>
This is the newsgroup of the Internet Amateur Mathematics Society,
moderated by <a href="mailto:benjie@hh.sbay.org">Benjie Chen</a>.
Extensive <a href="archive/iams/">archives</a> are available.

<li><a href="news:maus.mathe" name="maus.mathe">maus.mathe</a><br>
  German language version of sci.math.</li>

</ul>

<a name="email"></a>
<h2>Problem Columns via Electronic Mail</h2>
<ul>
<li>Stan Wagon's Problem of the Week</li>
Each week during the fall and spring semesters,
<a href="mailto:wagon@macalstr.edu">Stan Wagon</a> posts a Problem of the Week for students at Macalester College. This 
tradition was started in 1968 by Professor Joe Konhauser (recently deceased); Joe posted problems for 25 years and Stan took over in 1993.
These problems are meant to be accessible to first-year college students, so very little background is needed to understand or 
solve the problems.
<p>
Stan sends out the problems by e-mail as well (the mailing list 
currently has about 200 names), and if you would like to be
placed on the list, send a message
to that effect to Meridy Amsden at
<a href="mailto:amsden@macalstr.edu">amsden@macalstr.edu</a>.
The subject of the email message should be "wagon's problem list".
<a>
The  best of the over 700 problems used so far will appear in a book
co-authored by J. Konhauser, D. Velleman, and S. Wagon, titled
"Which Way Did the Bicycle Go?". It will be published by the
Mathematical Association of America and should be available by the
end of 1995.<p>

<li>The Internet Amateur Mathematics Society
<p>
Benjie Chen and the Internet Amateur Mathematics Society publish
math problems from time to time on their newsgroup and world wide web pages.
You can also receive this information via electronic mail.
Their mail list server is
<a href="mailto:listserv@hh.sbay.org">lstserv@hh.sbay.org</A>.

</ul>

<a name="wwwjnls"></a>
<h2>Journals with problem columns</h2>
		<ul>
<li><a HREF="http://www.digitas.org:80/tangents/">
Tangents</a>
Tangents Online is the electronic version of the Harvard-Radcliffe Mathematics
Bulletin.
It contains a problem column called Math Challenge Problem and Puzzles,
edited by Takara Stanley.
<li><a href="http://web.mit.edu/afs/athena/org/t/techreview/www/tr.html">
Technology Review</a><br>
The journal, Technology Review, has a problem column run by
<a href="http://cs.nyu.edu/cs/faculty/gottlieb/">Allan Gottlieb</a>.
Although this journal is now being published on the web, the web version
does not yet include the problem column, which only appears in the
alumni edition.
<a href="http://www.mathsoft.com/puzzle.html">Selected problems</a> are
reprinted at
<a href="http://www.mathsoft.com/">MathSoft's Web site</a>.
<li><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/math/mayhem.html">Mathematical Mayhem</a>
has several problem columns. It has its own web page, but the problems
are not yet on-line.
</u>
		<a name="bookstores"></a>
		<h2>On-line Bookstores that stock Problem Books</h2>
		<ul>
<li><a href=
"http://www.technical.powells.portland.or.us/stacks/science.math.html">Powell's
Technical Bookstore</a><br>
Check out listings under General/recreational
</ul>

<a name="information"></a>
<h2>Miscellaneous information</h2>
<ul>
  
<li>The University of Tennessee at Knoxville maintains
<a href="gopher://archives.math.utk.edu:70/">The Mathematics Archives</a>
which contains information about various
<a href="gopher://archives.math.utk.edu:70/11/teaching.materials/contests">mathematics contests</a>.</li>
  
<li>The <a href="gopher://gopher.maa.org:70/">MAA gopher</a> has information
about <a href="gopher://gopher.maa.org:70/11/student/Competitions">mathematics competitions</a>.</li>
  
<li>A <a href="gopher://ctdnet.acns.nwu.edu:70/11/The_Center_for_Talent_Development/Contests_and_Competitions/Math_and_Engineering/">list of math competitons</A>
is maintained by <a href="https://www.ctd.northwestern.edu">
The_Center_for_Talent_Development</a>.
  
<LI>Xah Lee and Michel Gallant are the sysops for
the Math Puzzles forum on compuserve (section 20 of the Science and Math Forum).
This is a bulletin board that discusses a wide variety of math puzzles.
They occasionally hold Recreational Math Puzzle Conferences.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.math.harvard.edu:80/~kedlaya/">Kiran S. Kedlaya</A> maintains an<A HREF="http://WWW.MATH.HARVARD.EDU:80/~kedlaya/competitions.html">archive</A>
containing problems and solutions from various competitions, such as the USAMO,
the IMO, and the Putnam Competitions.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.win.tue.nl/win/cs/pa/wstomv/">Tom Verhoeff</A>
maintains information about the
<A HREF="http://www.win.tue.nl/win/ioi/">International Olympiad in
Informatics</A>. He also has some information about the
<A HREF="http://www.win.tue.nl/win/ioi/imo/">International
Mathematical Olympiad</A>.
</ul>

